# Consequences of Children Not Liking to Share: An In-Depth Analysis

The ability to share is a fundamental aspect of social development in children, closely linked to the emergence of fairness, empathy, cooperation, and moral understanding. However, not all children naturally enjoy or are willing to share, especially at early developmental stages. This report explores the consequences of children not liking to share, drawing on empirical research and expert opinions to provide a comprehensive understanding of the social, emotional, and developmental implications. The analysis also considers the nuanced reasons behind children's reluctance to share and the broader context of sharing as a developmental milestone.

---

## 1. Understanding Children's Reluctance to Share

Young children, particularly toddlers and preschoolers, often exhibit possessiveness over their belongings, a behavior that is developmentally normative. This possessiveness is rooted in their egocentric worldview and limited cognitive capacities, such as an underdeveloped sense of time and fairness ([Education.com, n.d.](https://www.education.com/magazine/article/What_if_Child_Doesnt_Share/); [Greater Good Science Center, 2018](https://greatergood.berkeley.edu/article/item/why_is_your_preschooler_not_sharing)). For example, toddlers perceive a toy taken away as lost forever, which explains aggressive responses to sharing demands.

Moreover, children's sharing behavior is influenced by their cognitive abilities, such as counting and fairness understanding, which develop gradually. Research shows that young children may want to share but lack the "cognitive toolbox" to do so fairly ([Greater Good Science Center, 2018](https://greatergood.berkeley.edu/article/item/why_is_your_preschooler_not_sharing)). Temperament and social context also play roles; children are more willing to share with less threatening or younger peers and may be selective based on their relationship with the other child ([AskDrSears, n.d.](https://www.askdrsears.com/topics/parenting/discipline-behavior/morals-manners/11-ways-teach-your-child-share/)).

---

## 2. Social and Emotional Consequences of Not Liking to Share

### 2.1 Peer Relationships and Social Acceptance

One of the most significant consequences of children not liking to share is the impact on peer relationships and social acceptance. Children who consistently refuse to share may experience social rejection or isolation, as sharing is a key behavior that facilitates cooperation and friendship formation. The longitudinal study by Malti et al. (2012) found that feelings of social acceptance at age 6 strongly predicted sharing behavior at age 7, indicating that children who feel accepted are more willing to share valuable resources ([Malti et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0052017)).

Conversely, children who do not share may be perceived as less cooperative or generous, leading to fewer play opportunities and strained social interactions. This can create a negative feedback loop where social rejection further diminishes a child's motivation to share, potentially impacting their social-emotional development.

### 2.2 Development of Other-Regarding Preferences and Moral Growth

Sharing behavior is closely linked to the development of other-regarding preferences—concern for the welfare of others—which underpin fairness, care, and cooperation. Children who resist sharing may lag in developing these pro-social orientations. Malti et al. (2012) demonstrated that sharing increases significantly between ages 6 and 9 and is associated with early-developing sympathy towards anonymous others. Lack of sharing may therefore reflect or contribute to delayed moral development ([Malti et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0052017)).

Moreover, forced sharing, often used by parents or educators to encourage sharing, can backfire by teaching children that sharing is a coercive act rather than a voluntary expression of empathy and kindness. This may undermine the internal motivation necessary for genuine generosity and moral growth ([Verywell Family, 2021](https://www.verywellfamily.com/forcing-your-kid-to-share-4126426); [Center for Parenting Education, n.d.](https://centerforparentingeducation.org/library-of-articles/sibling-rivalry/sharing/)).

### 2.3 Emotional Responses: Resentment and Anger

When children are compelled to share before they are developmentally ready or against their will, they often experience negative emotions such as resentment, unfairness, and anger. These feelings can overshadow the positive emotions associated with kindness and generosity, potentially leading to behavioral issues and strained parent-child relationships ([Center for Parenting Education, n.d.](https://centerforparentingeducation.org/library-of-articles/sibling-rivalry/sharing/)).

Furthermore, children who are forced to share may learn maladaptive lessons, such as crying loudly to get what they want or believing that adults control all resource distribution, which can hinder their development of self-advocacy and fairness understanding ([Verywell Family, 2021](https://www.verywellfamily.com/forcing-your-kid-to-share-4126426)).

